bug.short_desc: Garbled tree window contents after scrolling

long_desc.thetext:
Hello,
This is a weird problem that so far shows up for me only with a specific OS&browser combination - namely, Gentoo-64&Firefox (any version from probably 17 to the current 34.whatever). On the same computer & under the same window manager etc, but using Chromium or Opera, it never happens. On the other hand, Firefox on a few other Linux boxes is OK. And nothing like this happens with any other website etc. So I realize this must be a very rare combination of various components that triggers the bug.
Anyhow, here is a proper description. I use the Tree widget with a vertical scroll bar. Scrolling with either mouse wheel or dragging the scrollbar sometimes results in a garbled tree content. This looks like a refresh/backingstore/sync issue, since after some delay (typically 2--3 seconds) the garbled area gets repainted automatically with no action from my side (just wait). Please see a few typical screenshots, using the <http://demo.qooxdoo.org/current/showcase/index.html#Tree> demo. 1.png, 2.png, and 3.png are screenshots taken immediately after the scrolling, and 1a.png, 2a.png, and 3a.png - a few seconds later.
Some more potentially useful info:
1. With both demos on that page, "Simple View" and "Detailed View", I am able to reproduce the bug, but not with <http://demo.qooxdoo.org/current/demobrowser/#widget~Tree.html>. Nor with any other scrollable widget.
2. In my own app, the bug happens practically 100% of the time I scroll a tree widget, while with <http://demo.qooxdoo.org/current/showcase/index.html#Tree> it happens about once in ten scrolls or so.
3. In my app, only the Modern theme is vulnerable; Indigo, Classic, and Simple are all OK.

Thanks for the detailed report. This look strange in deed but unfortunately we don't have access to such a system so we can't reproduce the issue here. Setting up such a system is too much effort for that edge case. As this is a rendering issue, I would try to trigger a browser rerendering (read the offsetHeight of the DOM node) and see of that fixes the problem.
